{"id":"2103.03362","submitter":"Anis Allagui","authors":"Anis Allagui and Ahmed S. Elwakil","title":"Information Encoding/Decoding using the Memory Effect in\n  Fractional-order Capacitive Devices","comments":"5 pages, 3 figures, Submitted on Jan 28, 2021 to ACS Applied\n  Electronic Materials - Manuscript ID: el-2021-00092h","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.app-ph eess.SP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In this study, we show that the discharge voltage pattern of a\nfractional-order supercapacitor from the same initial steady-state voltage into\na constant resistor is dependent on the past charging voltage profile. The\ncharging voltage was designed to follow a power-law function, i.e.\n$v_c(t)=V_{cc} \\left( {t}/{t_{ss}}\\right)^p \\;(0<t \\leqslant t_{ss})$, in which\n$t_{ss}$ (charging time duration between zero voltage to the terminal voltage\n$V_{cc}$) and $p$ ($0<p<1$) act as two variable parameters. We used this\nhistory-dependence of the dynamic behavior of the device to uniquely retrieve\ninformation pre-coded in the charging waveform pattern. Furthermore, we provide\nan analytical model based on fractional calculus that explains\nphenomenologically the information storage mechanism. The use of this intrinsic\nmaterial memory effect may lead to new types of methods for information storage\nand retrieval.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Feb 2021 03:16:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-03-08"}
